be determined on the basis of the degree of freedom. If the test statistic falls into the rejection region, the null hypothesis should be rejected, vice versa.

Ship Arrival Pattern Analysis

Ship arrival pattern is usually described by distribution function of the daily arrival vessels and the inter-arrival time between two ships. This paper collects the vessel arrival data of some domestic container terminals, such as Port NB, GZ, SZ, etc., then groups the sample data of the number of daily arrival vessels and the inter-arrival time respectively and draws frequency histogram. The sample data is supposed to follow Poisson, normal, negative-exponential and gamma distribution, and then tested by the Chi-Square test method at the 0.05 significance level, so as to determine the ship arrival pattern.
Port NB. Port NB, known for its container mainline harbor, integrates the estuary and gulf harbors into an organic whole in the Yangtze River Delta region. It remains the 4th in container throughput in China and is open to navigation to more than 600 ports in over 100 countries and regions around the world. Meanwhile, it owns ocean routes like the Mediterranean Sea routes, Europe routes, West America routes, South Africa route, Middle East routes, etc. and near-sea shipping lines like West Asia routes, as well as domestic routes and feeder routes. Its main business is to provide ocean transportation services, supplemented with short-range ocean and domestic transportation. By the end of 2010, the proportion of its ocean shipping reached up to 53.5%.
Take CMICT for example, this paper collects ship arrival data from May 2008 to May 2009, analyzes ship arrival pattern of container terminals in Port NB. The inspection results are shown in table 1.
(1) Distribution law of the number of daily arrival vessels Seen from table 1, the number of daily arrival vessels in CMICT follows Poisson distribution. The histogram and fitting curve are shown in figure 1(a). When Poisson distribution is assumed,

